<span id="freeTextContainer10346815539324255201"><strong>An old favourite</strong><br/><br/>I&apos;ve lost count of the number of times I&apos;ve read this book and it has been a few years since the last time. It holds my attention as much now as it did the first time, when I was a teenager. Into my 40&apos;s now, maturity has brought greater understanding of some of the themes but not lost any of the compelling story. The character of Killashandra delights me in many ways but also brings recognition of her flaws. McCaffrey was always a genius at creating human characters that you cou</span>
  <span id="freeText10346815539324255201" style="display:none"><strong>An old favourite</strong><br /><br />I've lost count of the number of times I've read this book and it has been a few years since the last time. It holds my attention as much now as it did the first time, when I was a teenager. Into my 40's now, maturity has brought greater understanding of some of the themes but not lost any of the compelling story. The character of Killashandra delights me in many ways but also brings recognition of her flaws. McCaffrey was always a genius at creating human characters that you could empathise with.</span>
