<div id="review_1960444070" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1960444070" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13363048-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1460762715p2/13363048.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1960444070?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/13363048-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13363048-michelle?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13363048-michelle?shelf=adult-fiction">adult-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1960444070" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5010278004177873500">This book was only 300 pages, but it seemed to go on foreeeever.<br/><br/>Alas, by the end, I did not care at all about what happened to our dear, over-dramatic heroine, Killashandra Ree (you can tell McCaffrey really loved writing that name, because her full name is used way more often than necessary).<br/><br/>Which was fine, because it&apos;s not like there was any tension anyway. To be fair, this is more of a character-based book than a plot-based one. Unfortunately, I didn&apos;t care much for the character. Killashandr</span>
  <span id="freeText5010278004177873500" style="display:none">This book was only 300 pages, but it seemed to go on foreeeever.<br /><br />Alas, by the end, I did not care at all about what happened to our dear, over-dramatic heroine, Killashandra Ree (you can tell McCaffrey really loved writing that name, because her full name is used way more often than necessary).<br /><br />Which was fine, because it's not like there was any tension anyway. To be fair, this is more of a character-based book than a plot-based one. Unfortunately, I didn't care much for the character. Killashandra is all ambition and superiority. You might say she has more "spirit" than "heart;" she shows few hints of caring at all about other people beyond what they can do for her, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[exception being perhaps when she saves Moksoon's life, though that action didn't make much sense to me from her end. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> This shouldn't affect her being an interesting (if not necessary likable) protagonist, but I realized by the end that pretty much all the other characters fell into the category of existing either to 1) admire Killashandra/sleep with her, or 2) be pettily jealous of Killashandra so she can demonstrate her superiority. Yeah, it's great that she goes for what she (impulsively decides she) wants, but mostly she's just incredibly lucky and "special." There's really no challenge.<br /><br />I would've liked more world-building, because the idea of crystal that must be sung to on a planet with symbiotic spores (or what have you) that have different effects on humans is kinda cool. Unfortunately, the book does feel a bit dated, having been written in the 80s and featuring references to such futuristic objects as a "vidifax" (you know, like a fax machine) and ubiquitous "printouts." Can't really fault McCaffrey for this, but it did feel clunky.<br /><br />Finally ... let's be honest, most of the book is just Killashandra eating, sleeping/resting/taking a bath, having sex, or staring at crystal. Boooring.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5010278004177873500" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


