    <a title="Marsha" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3098769-marsha"><img alt="Marsha" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/103587135?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marsha" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marsha" href="/user/show/3098769-marsha">Marsha</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3098769-marsha?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer103587135" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer653440984321647493">I remember being very fond of this book; I must have read it some time in my late teens or early 20&apos;s. Apparently, I had very good taste, because I enjoyed it just as much now as then. <br/><br/>It&apos;s a quick and engaging read. It maps the process of the primary character, Killashandra Ree, from her failure to make the grade as a lead operatic singer on her planet, through finding out about the profession of crystal singing, to her application, study and mastery of this dangerous pursuit. The reader learns</span>
  <span id="freeText653440984321647493" style="display:none">I remember being very fond of this book; I must have read it some time in my late teens or early 20's. Apparently, I had very good taste, because I enjoyed it just as much now as then. <br /><br />It's a quick and engaging read. It maps the process of the primary character, Killashandra Ree, from her failure to make the grade as a lead operatic singer on her planet, through finding out about the profession of crystal singing, to her application, study and mastery of this dangerous pursuit. The reader learns as she learns...the story peels away its layers. The prose is rich and colorful. The romantic aspect is believable and not overdone. <br /><br />This is a book that I'd come back to, rereading for pleasure. I'm glad there are two more books in the series that I've never read. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="653440984321647493" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


